	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The bit about online multiplayer NES games sounds like a fun experiment even though I doubt anyone would develop a NES MMO title, I'd love to see one. (Too few people would get the hardware for more than an experiment to take off, methinks).
<br />
<br />If you want to get the NES online I think you'd be going about it the wrong way and this sounds needlessly complex. Were I you I'd design an add-on like the FDS, in the same vein as the Famicom Network System, to interface the NES to an Ethernet network. I'm sure you could manage some text based browsing and playing online text based games like MUDs that way.
<br />
<br />I wouldn't go trying to render web pages on a system with a 1.79 MHz 6502 derivative. Although, if you're not using the sound components of the 2A03 for anything, there is no disadvantage to overclocking the crap out of it except for the potential to occasionally miss an IRQ or two. I've had the 2A03 CPU up to 4.2 MHz before <img src="./images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" /> That opens the door to a lot of fun weird ideas.
<br />
<br />But yeah, long story short whatever you build will have to be a completely discrete entity with its own RAM, network adapter, storage interface, and hell, maybe its own CPU. It would probably be a little crazy if it had more power under the hood than the NES though!

		

		</td>
	</tr>
